Overview

Introduction

There are few things in this world that are universally despised. City traffic. Wet socks. Global pandemics. And the subject of this memorandum, connecting flights at airports.

When I was a child, I often had to take connecting flights on my way to see family for the holidays (a very lucky problem to have!). My parents explained that doing so was necessary, that taking connecting flights saved money we needed to go on vacation in the first place. But I never understood how it could be less expensive to travel a longer distance than a nonstop, direct flight would take. My parents had lied to before (looking at you, Santa), so I was suspicious.

In this project, we plan to answer that childhood mystery by finding out what factors actually affect the price of a flight. Are connecting flights cheaper? Do we really save money by taking flights with multiple stops? Or is this theory full of hot air?

The Variables

In our journey through Kaggle, we discovered a mysterious man by the name of Shray Garg. Mr.Garg is a data analyst at Infosys and a Kaggle Expert, as he reports in his LinkedIn. The dataset he constructed lends credence to that claim, as it contains records for over 13,000 flight routes conducted in March-June 2019. Of those flights, 10,683 of them contain both their price and the number of stops on the way to the destination.

This dataset can be found here: https://www.kaggle.com/zwartfreak/airline-fare-prediction

Our initial dataset houses the following twelve variables:

  • Airline
  • Date_of_Journey
  • Source (city)
  • Destination (city)
  • Route (airport chain)
  • Departure Time
  • Arrival Time
  • Duration
  • Total number of stops
  • Additional info (in flight meals, baggage, etc)
  • Price

After data tidying, we reduce this total to the following nine variables:

  1. Airline : The name of the airline brand that sponsors our flight route. There are 12 unique airlines are in this dataset: Air Asia, Air India, GoAir, IndiGo, Jet Airways, Jet Airways Business, Multiple carriers, Multiple carriers Premium Economy, SpiceJet, Trujet, Vistara, and Vistara Premium Economy.

  2. Source (City of Origin) : The city that our flight route initially departs from. There are 5 cities of origin: Banglore, Chennai, Delhi, Kolkata, and Mumbai.

  3. Destination (City of Destination) : The city that our flight route finally arrive to. There are 6 cities in Destination: Banglore, Cochin, Delhi, Hyderabad, Kolkata, and New Delhi.

  4. DateID : A categorical conversion of the day of the year 2019 that the flight route departed, with Jan 1 having the DateID value 01 and December 31 having the DateID value 365. This dataset contains the information of flights from March 2019 through June 2019. Our dataset ranged from our first flight, DateID 60 (March 1st), to our last flight, DateID 178 (June 27th). This variable is not used in our models.

  5. Weekday: The day of week that the flight departed. This is a categorical variable with seven possible values: Friday, Monday, Saturday, Sunday, Thursday, Tuesday, and Wednesday.

  6. Holiday: Whether or not the flight took place within 2 days of a national holiday. (There are 3 observed national holidays in India between March and June).

  7. FlightWindow: The window in which the flight departed. There are four - Morning (4am to 10am), Midday (10am to 4pm), Evening (4pm to 10pm), Overnight(10pm to 4am)

  8. TotalStops: The total number of stops on flight. 0 indicates a direct flight, while a positive integer indicates layovers. The maximum value in our dataset is 4.

  9. FlightTime: The total amount of time our flight route spends, beginning when it departs from its source and ending when it arrives at its destination. Recorded in minutes.

  10. Price: The total cost of admission for our flight route. Recorded in Rupees.

The two variables most relevant for our purposes are the predictor variable Total number of stops and the response variable Price. All other variables are control variables, which we will do our best to minimize. Obviously, a longer flight on Christmas Eve is going to be more expensive than a short flight in mid-March, regardless of the number of stops. Our model will adjust for these discrepancies using linear regression.

Note that throughout this report, we use versions of a variable name (ie FlightTime vs Flight Time) interchangably. The official names, the ones used in our code, are those outlined in the list above.

Variable Transformations

You will notice that the variables DateID, Weekday, Holiday, FlightWindow, and FlightTime are not native to our original dataset. These five variables arise as transformations of our original columns.

DateID and Weekday originate from Date_Of_Journey and a 2019 calendar.

Holiday originates from DateID and a list of 2019 Indian holidays.

FlightWindow originates from DepartureTime.

FlightTime originates from Duration.

Dataset Cleanings

Our initial dataset as delivered by Mr.Garg is tidy, but it needed numerous cleanings and transformations to be converted into a format usable for our purposes.

Earlier, we referenced how there were 13354 total observations in our overall dataset, but only 10,683 usable observations. This is because our default dataset is already split into a 10,683-row Training set and a 2,671-row Test dataset. However, the test dataset does not contain values for price. Unfortunately, as we are attempting to predict price, this makes those observations unusable for our purposes. We declined to download the test dataset, along with its 10 columns (duplicates of our training datasets 11 columns sans price).

We were forced to remove the Additional Info column from our dataset. Unfortunately, not every airline logs its additional features, like in flight meals and baggage. The airlines who do log their info have no set standard as to what each term means. Does baggage refer to free checked bags? Free carry-ons? Extra space to place bags underneath seats? We dont know, and so we cannot safely use the column as a predictor.

We were able to determine that the Additional Info column was not filled out by every flight by looking at the red-eye descriptor. For some flights, this descriptor did not show up, despite the flight taking place during the Overnight period in FlightWindow. For other flights, it did. This discrepency further cemented our lack of faith in Additional Info providing clarity.

We had some data reading issues when it came to flights of less than one hour. Our model assumes that FlightTime is formatted as xh ym (X hours and Y minutes), but when x = 0, our default dataset only outputs the minutes. There was one flight that took only five minutes to complete, which caused our dataset to mistakenly print out that it took 0 minutes, a physical impossibility. This flight was changed manually to its correct value of 5 minutes. Interestingly, there were no other flights of a duration less than an hour long. We hypothesize that each airport is at least one hour away from the others, and that the five minute flight departed and arrived that the same airport.

Limitations

Our dataset has a limited scope. It only involves flights that took place within India, which could have a different economic model than North American brands. Our data is limited to a handful of brands and airports, limiting its scope further. The data collected is from 2019, before the coronavirus pandemic rattled the global economy.

Tidying the Data

Import Dataset

We start by importing Mr.Gargs dataset into our workspace.

# Read in the data
planes <- read.csv("planes.csv")
# head(planes)

Data Conversion

Here, we split the column Duration from its original format of Xh Ym into two columns; an hour column and a minute column. This is important so that we can convert the hours and minutes to a single measure of time FlightTime later. For example, 4h 15m would become 255m after our process is complete. The new column is christened FlightTime.

# We need to split the column 'Duration' so that we can convert it to time

# Label the columnnames

# removing the 'm' in Hours column
planes2$Min <- gsub("m", "", as.character(planes2$Min))

# Now coercing to numeric columns
planes2$Hours <- as.numeric(planes2$Hours)
planes2$Min <- as.numeric(planes2$Min)

# Changing NA's to Zero
planes2[is.na(planes2)] <- 0

# Creating a new vector in original planes df that totals the time in minutes
planes$FlightTime <- planes2$Hours*60+planes2$Min

#head(planes)

planes$FlightTime[planes$FlightTime == 0] <- 5

# bandaid for a strange one that got split badly since the flight time was only 5 min

We now need to split the column Total_Stops into a new numeric vector. This converts our data from strings like non-stop, 1 stop 2 stops, etc, into integers like 0, 1, 2, etc. This helps our later models understand that the number of stops exists quantitatively. Plus, it looks nicer!

# We need to split the column 'Total_Stops' so that we can have a separate column for numeric values
planes2 <- as_tibble(str_split_fixed(planes$Total_Stops, ' ', n=2))

# drop unnecessary column V2
planes2 <- subset(planes2, select = -V2)

# Convert to numeric
planes2$V1 <- as.numeric(planes2$V1)

# Changing NA's to Zero
planes2[is.na(planes2)] <- 0

# Adding to original DF
planes$TotalStops <- planes2$V1
#head(planes)

We now move on to tidying our Departure Time column, current name Dep_Times and later name FlightWindow. We go through the same process as with Duration / FlightTime in regards to splitting up the hour and minute values, but here, we use the hour column to create a new categorical variable.

We decided to group our departure times into four groups, to reduce our number of parameters and thus reduce variance in our model. Those four groups are Overnight (10 PM to 4 AM), Morning (4 AM to 10 AM), Midday (10 AM to 4 PM), and Evening (4 PM to 10 PM). The minute column is irrelevant, as our bins are arranged at the top of the hour. A flight at the top of the hour counts for the later time period: for example, a flight departing at 10 AM counts as Midday.

Note that all time-of-day measurements are taken according to IST, India Standard Time. Thankfully, it does not recognize daylight savings time, making our job easier.

# We now want to clean the Dep_Time column, first we split so we can isolate the hr and minutes
planes2 <- as_tibble(str_split_fixed(planes$Dep_Time, ':', n=2))
colnames(planes2) <- c('Hour', 'Min')

# We can look categorize times into (EarlyMorning, Midday, Evening, Late) or we can leave it like this for a second.

#head(planes2)

# Lets create factor levels based on time of day. We categorize between 4am - 10 am as Morning, 10am-4pm as midday, 4pm -10 pm as evening, 10pm to 4am as overnight.

# initializing a column using the character column Hour fir a FLIGHT WINDOW column
planes2$window <-planes2$Hour 

# Now we convert the column Hour to index our conditional statements. (Not converting will evaluate character value not NUMERIC)
planes2$Hour <- as.numeric(planes2$Hour)

# Might as well convert the min column too although we probably dont need either in the final dataset. Will delete as we go
planes2$Min <- as.numeric(planes2$Min)


# For loop to fill our initialized window column. 
for(i in 1:nrow(planes2)) {
  if (planes2[i,1] >= 4 & planes2[i,1] < 10){
    planes2[i,3] = "Morning"
  }else if (planes2[i,1] >= 10 & planes2[i,1] < 16){
    planes2[i,3] = "Midday"
  }else if (planes2[i,1] >= 16 & planes2[i,1] < 22){
    planes2[i,3] = "Evening"
  }else if (planes2[i,1] >= 22 | planes2[i,1] < 4){
    planes2[i,3] = "Overnight"
  }
}

#head(planes2)

planes$FlightWindow <- as.factor(planes2$window)

We clean the date column by splitting it into Months, Days, and Years. we can ignore the Years column, as every single flight in our dataset took place in the year 2019. We then combine Months and Days into a single column that describes the number of days that have passed in 2019, where January 1st is 1, January 2nd is 2, etc. This number becomes our DateID column.

DateID is not used in our model, but it is used to create two columns that will be used in our model: Holiday and Weekday.

# We now want to clean the date column, first we split so we can isolate the Months Days Years

colnames(planes3) <- c('Day', 'Month', 'Year')

planes3$Day <- as.numeric(planes3$Day)
planes3$Month <- as.numeric(planes3$Month)
planes3$Year <- as.numeric(planes3$Year)
planes3$numdate <- planes3$Day

for(i in 1:nrow(planes3)) {
  if (planes3[i,2] == 03){
    planes3[i,4] = planes3[i,4] + 31 + 28
  }else if (planes3[i,2] == 04){
    planes3[i,4] = planes3[i,4] + 31 + 28 + 31
  }else if (planes3[i,2] == 05){
    planes3[i,4] = planes3[i,4] + 31 + 28 + 31 + 30
  }else if (planes3[i,2] == 06){
    planes3[i,4] = planes3[i,4] + 31 + 28 + 31 + 30 + 31

Here, we create a new column Holidays. This variable designates each day in the week leading up to the Holiday as a Yes, and all other days as a No. This should help adjust for increased prices leading up to those times.

# There are 2 national holidays between march and June in india in 2019
# April 14 (which is denoted as 104 in numdate)
# April 19 (which is denoted as 109)
# June 4-5 (denoted 155-156)
# holiday travel often occurs 1-2 days prior, so we reserve 102-106, 107-111 as holiday, and 151-158)

planes3$Holiday <- as.factor((planes3$numdate >= 102) & (planes3$numdate<=111) | (planes3$numdate >= 151 & (planes3$numdate <= 158)))

# This means that a remainder of 5 will be saturday, 6 will be sunday, 0 will be monday, 1 will be tuesday, 2 will be wednesday and 3 will be thursday.

planes3$remainders <- planes3$numdate %% 7

# head(planes3)

for(i in 1:nrow(planes3)) {

Finalize Dataset

Here, we alter the column order into a more intuitive formate, rewrite the data frame planes, and turn Holidays binary from TRUE and FALSE into a prettier Yes and No.

# Create a list with the order of columns

# Rewrite data frame planes
planes <- planes[,col_order]

# make the holiday column prettier
levels(planes$Holiday) <- c("No", "Yes")

Exploratory Data Analysis

It is time for our exploratory data analysis, where we use the flashiest tool in the staticians arsenal: drumroll Visualizations! This will allow us to confirm our dataset will function well for our models, determine what our models should be, and get cool graphics to show people who dont want to read thousands of words to learn about airplanes.

Pairs of Variables

First, lets see each plane pair using the pairs.panels function:

# Visualizing the data

pairs.panels(planes)

This plane pair plot shows the interaction between each pair of variables in our dataset. On the upper-left to lower-right diagonal, there is a histogram of each variable. Below the diagonal, we see the two variables plotted against each other, with a line of best fit outlined in red. Above the diagonal, we see a real number corresponding to the Pearson correlation between the two variables.

Note that the Pearson correlation \(r\) is not the same thing as the coefficient of determination \(R^2\). The Pearson correlation is used for finding patterns, while the coefficient of determination is used for evaluating the strenth of a model. We will be seeing the coefficient of determination below, in the Modeling section of this report.

Most of our pairs of variables have weak to no correlation. However, there are a few exceptions we would like to highlight:

Source and Destination are strongly correlated, with a Pearson correlation of 0.59. This makes sense; connected cities (geographically, politically, culturally) will likely follow similar paths.

Our strongest corrlelation is between Total Stops and Flight Time. This also makes sense; if you have to stop at multiple airports, the total amount off time your trip will take should increase in response. This is further exacerbated by the fact that Flight Time tracks time from departure to arrival, including time when the plane is sitting idle at a connecting airport.

Significantly, there are strong positive correlation between Price and Total Stops (0.60). There is a similarly strong positive correlation between Price and FlightTime (0.51). This doesnt itself show that Price increases as the number of stops increase, due to the strongly correlating factors of FlightTime, and the lack of controlling for effects such as Holiday, Weekday, Airline, etc. Still, its interesting to note during our pattern recognition stage.

# Visualizing the price in histogram

Jet Airways Business

What is up with Jet Airways Business? It is so much more expensive than every other airplane brand! After some research, we discovered that Jet Airways Business is an offshoot of Jet Airways catered towards business-class flights. Theyre serving a luxury market that completely differs from the rest of our airlines.

Interestingly, Multiple Carriers Premium Economy and Vistara Premium Economy do not have the same radical price increase. We believe that these offshoot brands offer small perks like extra legroom rather than the massive luxury boots that Jet Airways Business offers.

Jet Airways Business status as a business-class-only brand means their flights are not applicable to the economic models of economy class flights. They only contribute a small handful of flights into our dataset, but those flights massively influence our visualizations, overcentralizing our dataset in its image. We must remove Jet Airways Business from our dataset.

## removing Jet Airways business
planes <- planes%>%
  filter(planes$Airline != 'Jet Airways Business')

Modeling

Ridge Regression

Setup

We begin by splitting our dataset into a training and a test set for our various models. We decided to randomly sample 80% of our dataset to turn into the training set, and leave the remaining 20% as the test set. Because of our large number of observations, we are able to use a larger proportion of our observations to fuel our training set. Our test set still has over 2,000 unique observations to its own, so it will be sufficient to test our more refined, powerful models.

# set seed for reproducibility
set.seed(123)

# model matrix function produces a matrix corresponding to all 33 predictors and automatically transforms any qualitative variables to dummy variables
x = model.matrix(Price ~., planes)[, -1]
y = planes$Price

# split the data by randomly selecting 80 percent as training, remainder to test
train <- sample(1:nrow(x), 0.8*nrow(x))
test <- (-train)

x.train = x[train,]
y.train = y[train]
x.test = x[test,]
y.test = y[test]

We then fit a basic ridge regression to use as a skeleton for later, more refined models.

# fit a ridge regression model
grid = 10^seq(10, -2, length = 100)
ridge_mod = glmnet(x, y, alpha = 0, lamda = grid)

Fact-Finding Queries

We run a variety of exploratory queries to learn more about the model. Theyre commented out for this report, since they dont contribute to the building of the model itself.

L1 and L2 are the different weights used for the lasso and ridge regression, respectively. We want to verify that as lambda value gets bigger (lambda increases), the L2 norm squared of the coefficient estimates decreases.

pred <- predict(object = ridge_mod, newx  = x)

Next, let us fit a more complex ridge regression model on the lab-recommended lambda of \(\lambda = 4\).

# fit a ridge regression model on the training set and evaluate its MSE on the test set, using lambda = 4

ridge.mod=glmnet(x.train, y.train, alpha=0, lambda=grid)
ridge.pred = predict(ridge.mod, s=4, newx = x[test,])

# Since lambda is is large it tends to force the coefficients to be very small (close to 0) and therefore we would expect getting a model containing only an intercept. This is equivalent to fitting a constant model whose best choice is the mean of the training data. The following results indicates our conjecture is valid

Since lambda is is large it tends to force the coefficients to be very small (close to 0) and therefore we would expect getting a model containing only an intercept. This is equivalent to fitting a constant model whose best choice is the mean of the training data. And as expected, our training MSE and test MSE very similar. This indicates both that our large lambda does hinge our model around an intercept, and that this lambda is too large to serve as a useful Ridge model.

Lets now check how ordinary least squares regression works for our model.

# Checking to see if there's any benefit of lambda = 4

ridge.pred = predict(ridge.mod, s=0, newx = x[test,])
mean((ridge.pred-y.test)^2) # Get MSE
[1] 9452480

Our least-squares regression method gives us a MSE of \(9,452,480\). This is much lower than the \(21,941,791\) of our large-lambda value, and indicates a partial-pooling style approach works best in this case.

Cross validation

Let us now scientifically choose the best tuning parameter instead of relying on the lab-recommended, arbitrary \(\lambda = 4\).

set.seed(123)
cv.out.ridge = cv.glmnet(x.train, y.train, alpha = 0)
plot(cv.out.ridge)
abline(v=log(cv.out.ridge$lambda.min), col= "red", lwd = 3, lty = 2)

#dim(x.train)
#head(x.train)

This graph shows us our given MSE across different values of \(\log{\lambda}\). The constant \(30, 30, 30, 30, 30\) at the top of the graph refers to the number of predictors in our dataset, counting our categorical variables seperately for each classification they include.

# get the best lambda 
bestlam = cv.out.ridge$lambda.min
bestlam
[1] 274.9703

We find that our best lambda value for a ridge regression is \(274.9703\).

ridge.pred = predict(ridge.mod, s=bestlam, newx = x[test,])
mse <- mean((ridge.pred-y.test)^2) # Get MSE
# take the square root
rmse <- sqrt(mse)
rmse
[1] 3112.912

Our best-value lambda Ridge model rMSE, \(3074.839\), is slightly higher than with simple ordinary-least-squares (OLS) regression, \(3074.489\).

A case study in our notes indicates that OLS is ideal when the underlying relationship is Linear and we have n>>p.But if n is not much larger than p or p>n (unfeasible for OLS), there can be a lot of variability in the fit which can result in either overfitting and very poor predictive ability.

  • Source for quote: https://rstudio-pubs-static.s3.amazonaws.com/257535_4218def5fb0945a7a5c09126f385aa59.html#references

We likely have a dataset that ridge regression is not suited to solve. This is further corroborated by the contextual evidence of the strong correlations between Price and TotalStops/FlightTime that we found in our EDA.

Nevertheless, we shall proceed with our ridge regression for purposes of understanding machine learning.

The Lasso (lab 5 section 3)

Graphics

Let us begin by creating a coefficient plot for the dataset, across different log lambda values.

lasso.mod <- glmnet(x.train, y.train, alpha=1, lambda = grid)
plot(lasso.mod, xvar = "lambda", label = TRUE)

# Cross validation

set.seed(123)
cv.out.lasso = cv.glmnet(x.train, y.train, alpha = 1)
plot(cv.out.lasso)
abline(v = log(cv.out.lasso$lambda.min), col = 'red', lwd=3, lty = 2)

Our first graphic shows us the coefficients attached to our model as affected by \(\log(\lambda)\). The second shows us the mean squared error of the same model as affected by \(\log(\lambda)\)

Just like in Ridge regression, the numbers at the top of the graph represent the number of variables remaining in the dataset. Unlike in the Ridge regression, this number decreases as \(\log{\lambda}\) increases, eventually neutralizing down to \(0\). This is because, while Ridge regression lowers coefficients to negligable levels, Lasso regression lowers them all the way down to \(0\), effectively making the variable affected by the coefficient cease to exist.

Calculations

bestlam = cv.out.lasso$lambda.min

rmse
[1] 3075.986

And our lambda gives us a mean squared error of \(3075.986\). This is slightly worse than our Ridge MSE, \(3074.839\), and our OLS MSE, \(3074.489\).

Linear Model

Exploration of Linearity

Lets recall our pairs panel:

pairs.panels(planes)

Recall that our response variable Price was heavily right skewed. To fit our linear models, we will log-transform Price, our Y variable.

# Copying the planes data into a new df
planestransformed <- planes #normalized here

planestransformed$Price <- log(planestransformed$Price)

We saw a high correlation between total stops and flight time in our EDA, so we may encounter singularities in our model. We also see that Source and Destination is pretty highly correlated, so we can consider removing one or exploring an interaction with both. Therefore, we will fit a variety of nested models.

Fitting Nested Models

We will fit nine nested models: fullfit (stands for fully fitted), which uses every variable), and redmod 1-8 (stands for reduced model), eliminating strategic variables based on our datasets context as representing planes.

# Fitting full linear model with log price since it was not normally distributed

fullfit <- lm(Price ~ Airline + Source + Destination + Weekday + Holiday + FlightWindow + TotalStops + FlightTime, data = planestransformed)

summary(fullfit)$adj.r.squared 
[1] 0.717445
# Plot residuals

qqPlot(fullfit$residuals)

[1] 10048  4283
#shapiro
hist(fullfit$residuals)

The residuals look fairly normally distributed. Because of that, we can move on to a modified backwards-stepwise method for reducing our models parameters. Note that our adjusted \(R^2\) for the full-fit model is \(0.717445\).

We want to remove either Destination or Source from our model, as they have a strong correlation identified in our EDA, and correlation can negatively affect linear models. For our first model, redmod1, lets look at removing Source.

# Fit a reduced model removing source
redmod1 <- lm(Price~Airline + Destination + Weekday + Holiday + FlightWindow + TotalStops + FlightTime, data = planestransformed)
summary(redmod1)$adj.r.squared 
[1] 0.717445

Our adjusted R Squared, \(0.717445\), didnt change. We can compare to a model removing Destination instead:

# Fit a reduced model removing Destination
redmod2 <- lm(Price~Airline + Source + Weekday + Holiday + FlightWindow + TotalStops + FlightTime, data = planestransformed)

summary(redmod2)$adj.r.squared 
[1] 0.6974279

The adjusted Rsquared for our redmod2 model, \(06974279\) is worse than in redmod1. Therefore, we choose to keep Destination over Source in our model parameters.

Our second strong correlation is between FlightTime and TotalStops. We want to remove one of the two so that we avoid the strong correlation issues. Lets first try removing TotalStops:

# Remove Stops
redmod3 <- lm(Price~Airline + Destination + Weekday + Holiday + FlightWindow  + FlightTime, data = planestransformed)
summary(redmod3)$adj.r.squared 
[1] 0.6699248

Now lets try removing FlightTime:

# Fit a model removing FlightTime
redmod4 <- lm(Price~Airline + Destination + Weekday + Holiday + FlightWindow  + FlightTime, data = planestransformed)

summary(redmod4)$adj.r.squared 
[1] 0.6699248

Both removals lower our adjusted \(R^2\) compared to leaving both in. Lets investigate if there is an interaction effect between the two:

# interaction
redmod5 <- lm(Price~Airline +Destination + Weekday + Holiday + FlightWindow + TotalStops + FlightTime + TotalStops*FlightTime, data = planestransformed)

summary(redmod5)$adj.r.squared 
[1] 0.7235725

This model appears to have the highest Adjusted R-squared, at \(0.7235725\). Therefore, we will keep both TotalStops and FlightTime in our model, and add in an interaction term between the two.

Lets try removing some other variables that may add noise, like Holiday, Weekday, and FlightWindow:

# We try removing some other variables like Holiday and Weekday and FlightWindow

# remove Holiday
redmod6 <- lm(Price~Airline + Destination + Weekday  + FlightWindow + TotalStops + FlightTime + TotalStops*FlightTime, data = planestransformed)

summary(redmod6)$adj.r.squared 
[1] 0.7230584
# remove Weekday
redmod7 <- lm(Price~Airline + Destination + Holiday  + FlightWindow + TotalStops + FlightTime + TotalStops*FlightTime, data = planestransformed)

summary(redmod7)$adj.r.squared 
[1] 0.7118374
# remove FlightWindow
redmod8 <- lm(Price~Airline + Destination + Weekday  + Holiday + TotalStops + FlightTime + TotalStops*FlightTime, data = planestransformed)

No particular model seems to be worse in normality than others. Therefore, we compare our 9 linear models by error rates to determine which one to use as our final linear model. Some of those error rate statistics include \(AIC\), \(BIC\), and \(R^2\) values.

# We can compare our 9 linear models 

#calculate AIC of each model

#this will create a dataframe whose rownames are the models, with columns for the df and AIC of each model
result <- AIC(fullfit, redmod1, redmod2, redmod3, redmod4, redmod5, redmod6, redmod7, redmod8)

#add other metrics to your table
#make sure you keep your models in the same order here as they were when you created your results table
models <- list(fullfit, redmod1, redmod2, redmod3, redmod4, redmod5, redmod6, redmod7, redmod8)

#add a column for BIC to the results
result$BIC <- sapply(models, BIC) 

model_summary <- lapply(models, summary)

#now we will use a for loop to easily extract the R^2 and adj R^2 value for each model from its summary, and store them in new columns in the results table

for(i in 1:length(models)){ #this creates a variable i that starts with the value i=1
  result$rsq[i] <- model_summary[[i]]$r.squared #we assign the rsq value from model i to the i'th row of the column 'rsq' in the table 'results'
  result$adj_rsq[i] <- model_summary[[i]]$adj.r.squared #same for adjusted rsq
} #now we go back to the beginning of the for-loop, add 1 to the value of i, and do everything again


kable(result, digits = 9, align = "c") #We see that redmod8 has the lowest AIC and BIC values and the highest R^2 so we found our model.

K-Fold Cross-Validation

As a way to double-check our work, we used K-fold cross-validation to verify our R^2 value.

#Split the data let's do 80 20

# setting seed for reproducibility
set.seed(666)
#separate the data into a training set (most of the data) and a test set (a few observations, or <20% of rows)
splitter <- sample(1:nrow(planestransformed), 0.2*nrow(planestransformed), replace = F) #pick 30 random rows from planes to reserve as test data
lm.train <- planestransformed[-splitter,] #leave those rows out of the training data
lm.test <- planestransformed[splitter,] #use them to create a set of test data
lm.test <- cbind(sampleID = rownames(lm.test), lm.test)
rownames(lm.test) <-1:nrow(lm.test)

# Define training control
train.control <- trainControl(method = "cv", 
                              number = 10)
# Train the model
model <- train(Price ~Airline + Destination + Weekday  + Holiday + TotalStops + FlightTime + TotalStops*FlightTime, data = lm.train, method = "lm", trControl = train.control)
# Summarize the results
summary(model)$adj.r.squared 
[1] 0.7211768

This K-fold cross-validation verified our seemingly scaled \(R^2\) value. While the numbers are not exactly the same, resting at \(0.7236327\) for our model and \(0.7211768\) for our cross-validation, is is a result of our fitted model redmod being fit on all \(10,677\) observations in our dataset, while the training model used for k-fold cross-validation is only fit on the \(8,541\) observations in its training set.

Complications with Trujet

planes_lm = lm(Price ~ ., data = planes_trn)
#planes_lm_pred = predict(planes_lm, newdata = planes_tst) # THROWS AN ERROR!!!!
#plot(planes_lm_pred, planes_tst$Price, xlab = "Predicted", ylab = "Actual")
#abline(0, 1)

For our decision tree models, we need to drop the Trujet airline. There is only one observation of this airline, so it cannot coexist in both the training and test datasets. This makes it almost impossible to work with, and since it exists in less than 1/10000 of our data points, the simplest solution is to remove it from our dataset.

Note that while removing problematic observations is usually a faux pas in the world of statistical modeling, it makes sense in context. We are trying to build a model to predict Price, and one of our ways of doing so is in our airline brand. An airline brand with only one flight cannot predict anything, and just introduces uncertainty similar to Jet Airways Business.

# filter
planes_tst <- planes_tst%>%
  filter(Airline!="Trujet")

# plot
planes_lm = lm(Price ~ ., data = planes_trn)
planes_lm_pred = predict(planes_lm, newdata = planes_tst)
plot(planes_lm_pred, planes_tst$Price, xlab = "Predicted", ylab = "Actual")
abline(0, 1)

rmse(planes_lm_pred, planes_tst$Price)
[1] 3075.063

We arrive at a test rMSE of \(3075.063\). Note that our previous rMSE for our Goldilocks dataset was \(3077.688\), so removing Trujet led to a very small improvement in our rMSE. This completes our single pruned tree model!

Wait a second

Whats up with the linear rMSE?

Our linear models rMSE is far, far lower than every other result. We suspect that this rMSE value is scaled or normalized in some way that the rest of our models error rates are not. This is likely a mistake in our coding, due to a regressive models being outside the scope of the project this report was created for. Please have pity on us, for we are but lowly undergraduate students!

We also see a grouping of many rMSE around the value \(3075\). This is beause there are many similar models here. OLS, Lasso, and Ridge all work in very similar ways, and Goldilocks is just the Single Tree with Trujet included. Instead of being 5 models hovering around the same rMSE value, its derivations of 2 models - a much more likely event.

Quantitative Results

Due to the possibility of scaling, we believe that our Random Forest model is the most accurate for predicting the price of a future airplane route based on its other information.

While Random Forest may be the most accurate, Its Just That Simple deserves a shout-out for being the simplest to understand. Its just two questions! Is your flight short? Well, then its gonna be cheap. No? Well, is it on a budget airline brand? If yes, itll cost you a medium amount. If not, better pony up the dough, cowboy!

As our dataset was on Kaggle, we were able to see a few people had worked on the same data set we had. Every single one of them relied on a random forest method as their primary modeling tool, and every single one picked Python as their language of choice rather than R, as we did.

Final Word

When my parents said something that I didnt like to hear, like Eat your vegetables or You cant vote yet, youre a literal child, my first line of defense was usually to ask them why that is. I assume that is what I did in the airport, on our way to visit our relatives. And I imagine their response to me was what it usually was when they didnt have energy to deal with my antics: Ryan, its complicated.

Well, Mom and Dad, you were right. It is complicated. Complex-sounding questions, like Is price positively correlated with total number of stops for the average flight in India from March to June 2019 logged by Shray Garg on Kaggle, have simple answers, like Yes they are! But simple-sounding questions, like Do we have to take connecting flights to save money?, have complex answers.

As a child, I thought the world was easy to understand. Only now, as an adult, do I begin to understand just how much I was asking to know as a child, and how little we have just begun to understand.

Those darn kids and their naive curiosities! Personally, I blame the Googles!
